---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

// Divergent-clocks infographic data. x() maps a year onto the drawing width, so the lanes
// share one axis and the divergence is read off their milestone positions.
const YMIN = 2024;
const YMAX = 2035;
const X0 = 118;
const X1 = 690;
const x = (y: number) => X0 + ((y - YMIN) / (YMAX - YMIN)) * (X1 - X0);
const ticks = [2024, 2026, 2028, 2030, 2032, 2034, 2035];
const lanes = [
  { label: 'European Union', color: '#5b54a8', y: 66, from: 2025, to: 2035,
    marks: [{ yr: 2030, tag: 'milestone' }, { yr: 2035, tag: 'target' }] },
  { label: 'France', color: '#5b54a8', y: 108, from: 2024, to: 2032, hollow: true,
    marks: [{ yr: 2025, tag: 'hybridise' }, { yr: 2030, tag: 'standalone, not before' }] },
  { label: 'United States', color: '#2b4c7e', y: 150, from: 2025, to: 2035,
    marks: [{ yr: 2027, tag: 'procurement gate' }, { yr: 2030, tag: '' }, { yr: 2035, tag: 'complete' }] },
  { label: 'China, SM-series', color: '#7a3b5e', y: 192, from: 2024, to: 2035, arrow: true,
    marks: [] },
];
---

<Base
  title="One shared core, many wrappers"
  description="A QSC Atlas commentary on the fragmentation of the post-quantum transition, and how it is governed through a network of expectations rather than a central authority."
>
  <div class="container commentary">
    <p class="kicker">QSC Atlas commentary</p>
    <h1>One shared core, many wrappers</h1>
    <p class="standfirst prose">
      Why the post-quantum transition is fragmenting, and how it is governed all the same.
    </p>

    <p class="prose">
      One set of algorithms now sits underneath almost every national plan for post-quantum
      cryptography. When a United States federal agency published three standards in August 2024, a
      contested question became a settled technical fact, and within months those choices were in
      European certification catalogues, in national guidance from Paris to Bonn, and in the browsers
      shipping to the world. The core is shared. What surrounds it is not.
    </p>

    <h2>The wrappers: an instrument cascade</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      The same algorithms arrive wrapped in very different instruments. In the European Union they are
      becoming binding through NIS2 and DORA and, from December 2027, the Cyber Resilience Act, though
      rarely by name. The obligation is carried by an undefined phrase, state of the art, whose
      cryptographic content is supplied by an interpretive layer of certification guidance that sits
      between legislation and practice. Elsewhere the same core is wrapped in soft national roadmaps,
      and across much of the world in nothing at all. What an organisation must do depends less on the
      mathematics, which is common, than on the jurisdiction it operates in, which is not. This is the
      instrument cascade: from an undefined legal standard down to a de facto migration obligation,
      with the operative rule written in the interpretive layer rather than the statute.
    </p>

    <h2>The clocks diverge</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      The timetables fragment as sharply as the instruments. The European Union coordinates to 2030 and
      2035; France works to a phased, not-earlier-than schedule; the United States gates procurement
      through executive deadlines, one of which moved backwards in June 2025 when an order removed a
      post-quantum procurement requirement; China runs a separate SM-series track. The same migration
      therefore runs to different clocks in different places, and the deadlines are not simply
      forecasts. They are coordination devices.
    </p>

    <figure class="tl">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 236" role="img" aria-labelledby="tl-title tl-desc" class="tl-svg">
        <title id="tl-title">Divergent clocks: post-quantum milestones by bloc</title>
        <desc id="tl-desc">
          A shared 2024 to 2035 timeline with separate lanes for the European Union, France, the
          United States and China, showing how their milestones fall in different years.
        </desc>
        {
          ticks.map((t) => (
            <g>
              <line x1={x(t)} y1="44" x2={x(t)} y2="208" class="tl-grid" />
              <text x={x(t)} y="226" class="tl-year" text-anchor="middle">{t}</text>
            </g>
          ))
        }
        {
          lanes.map((ln) => (
            <g>
              <text x="8" y={ln.y + 4} class="tl-lane">{ln.label}</text>
              <line x1={x(ln.from)} y1={ln.y} x2={x(ln.to)} y2={ln.y} class="tl-base" style={`stroke:${ln.color}`} />
              {ln.arrow && (
                <polygon
                  points={`${x(ln.to)},${ln.y - 4} ${x(ln.to) + 9},${ln.y} ${x(ln.to)},${ln.y + 4}`}
                  style={`fill:${ln.color}`}
                />
              )}
              {ln.arrow && <text x={x(2033)} y={ln.y - 11} class="tl-tag" text-anchor="middle">ongoing, no fixed end</text>}
              {
                ln.marks.map((m) => (
                  <g>
                    <circle
                      cx={x(m.yr)}
                      cy={ln.y}
                      r="5"
                      class={ln.hollow ? 'tl-dot is-hollow' : 'tl-dot'}
                      style={ln.hollow ? `stroke:${ln.color}` : `fill:${ln.color}`}
                    />
                    {m.tag && <text x={x(m.yr)} y={ln.y - 11} class="tl-tag" text-anchor="middle">{m.tag}</text>}
                  </g>
                ))
              }
            </g>
          ))
        }
      </svg>
      <figcaption>
        The same core, different clocks. The European Union coordinates to 2030 and 2035; France runs
        a phased, not-earlier-than schedule; the United States gates procurement in 2027 and aims to
        finish by 2035; China runs a separate SM-series track. One executive order removed a United
        States procurement requirement in June 2025.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>Governing by expectation</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      This is where the transition is most unusual. Its governance runs on expectations rather than on
      an observed threat. Climate governance also coordinates through shared projections, but there the
      danger is visible: temperatures rise, ice retreats. Quantum-safe governance has no such
      observable; the cryptographically relevant quantum computer has not arrived, and may not for
      years. The deadlines do their work anyway, because expectations are performative. They cascade
      vertically, a revised hardware estimate registering at once in Washington's gates and Brussels'
      milestones, and they align horizontally, as when four national agencies co-signed a single
      position in January 2024 that confined quantum key distribution to niche uses and named
      post-quantum migration the priority. Coordination happens without a coordinator.
    </p>

    <h2>The failure mode is congestion, not absence</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      A network of expectations can fail, and its failure mode is congestion rather than a missing
      authority. The financial sector already faces DORA, national supervisors, G7 guidance and
      sectoral roadmaps at once, and the result is deferral: ENISA finds only a small share of European
      stakeholders have begun to migrate. The answer is not necessarily a central authority. It is to
      make the state of the transition common knowledge, who stands where, on which instrument, to what
      clock.
    </p>

    <p class="prose close">
      One shared core, many wrappers, held loosely together by a network of expectations. The Atlas
      maps the wrappers, country by country, so the fragmentation can at least be read.
    </p>

    <h2>Sources</h2>
    <ul class="sources">
      <li>NIST, FIPS 203, 204 and 205: post-quantum cryptography standards (August 2024).</li>
      <li>European Union: Directive (EU) 2022/2555 (NIS2); Regulation (EU) 2022/2554 (DORA); Regulation (EU) 2024/2847 (Cyber Resilience Act), applicable from December 2027.</li>
      <li>ENISA, European Union Agency for Cybersecurity: cryptographic certification (EUCC) and post-quantum readiness surveys (with ISACA).</li>
      <li>NIS Cooperation Group: A Coordinated Implementation Roadmap for the Transition to Post-Quantum Cryptography (2026), setting the 2030 and 2035 milestones.</li>
      <li>ANSSI (France): position on the transition to post-quantum cryptography, a phased not-earlier-than roadmap.</li>
      <li>United States: NSA Commercial National Security Algorithm Suite 2.0 (CNSA 2.0), gating procurement from 2027 with completion by 2035; and Executive Order 14306 (6 June 2025), which amended Executive Order 14144 and removed the mandatory post-quantum procurement requirement.</li>
      <li>China: OSCCA SM-series national cryptographic algorithms.</li>
      <li>ANSSI, BSI, the Netherlands NLNCSA and the Swedish National Communications Security Authority: joint position paper on quantum key distribution (January 2024), prioritising post-quantum migration.</li>
      <li>G7 Cyber Expert Group: statement on quantum computing risks to the financial sector (2024).</li>
      <li>Bradford, A. (2020). The Brussels Effect. Oxford University Press.</li>
      <li>Budde, B., and Konrad, K. (2019). Tentative governing in a dynamic network of expectations. Research Policy (the governance of expectations).</li>
      <li>CEPS: Pupillo, L., et al. (2025). Strengthening the EU Transition to a Quantum-Safe World, Task Force report.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="attribution">
      A QSC Atlas commentary, drawing on the CEPS Task Force on Strengthening the EU Transition to a
      Quantum-Safe World (2025). <a href="/methodology">How the Atlas classifies countries &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .commentary {
    max-width: 44rem;
  }
  .kicker {
    font-family: var(--font-label);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-label);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);
  }
  .commentary h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-reading);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: var(--type-scene, 2rem);
    line-height: 1.1;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-4);
  }
  .standfirst {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-8);
  }
  .commentary h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-reading);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    margin: var(--space-10) 0 var(--space-3);
  }
  .commentary .prose + .prose {
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
  }
  .close {
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .attribution {
    margin-top: var(--space-10);
    padding-top: var(--space-5);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
  }
  .attribution a {
    color: var(--ink);
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  /* Divergent-clocks timeline */
  .tl {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
  }
  .tl-svg {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    display: block;
  }
  .tl-grid {
    stroke: var(--hairline);
    stroke-width: 1;
  }
  .tl-base {
    stroke-width: 2;
    opacity: 0.5;
  }
  .tl-dot.is-hollow {
    fill: var(--paper);
    stroke-width: 2;
  }
  .tl-lane {
    font-family: var(--font-instrument);
    font-size: 12px;
    fill: var(--ink);
  }
  .tl-year {
    font-family: var(--font-instrument);
    font-size: 11px;
    fill: var(--ink-muted);
  }
  .tl-tag {
    font-family: var(--font-instrument);
    font-size: 10.5px;
    fill: var(--ink-muted);
  }
  .tl figcaption {
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
  }

  /* Sources */
  .sources {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 0;
    padding-left: var(--space-5);
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--space-2);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
  }
  .sources li {
    line-height: 1.45;
  }
</style>
